%erg 0.1
Title: Check Zotero library before fetching to avoid re-download
Created: 2026-07-08
Author: claude

--- log ---
2026-07-08T20:06Z claude created

--- body ---
## Context
DOIfetch has no knowledge of the user's Zotero library. The only dedup today
is a filesystem check in each fetcher: build a filename from the paper *title*
(`clean_filename(title).pdf`), and if that exact file already exists in
`PAPERS_DIR` and is a valid PDF, return `"skipped"`. Consequences:

- A paper already in Zotero (but not sitting in `PAPERS_DIR`) is refetched.
- The skip check keys on the cleaned *title*, not the DOI, so any title-string
  mismatch defeats it even for papers DOIfetch itself downloaded.

For robust use against an existing reference library, DOIfetch should consult
Zotero first and skip papers already held, keyed on DOI (with title as
fallback). This avoids hammering Sci-Hub/ISTEX/etc. for documents the user
already owns.

## Relevant files
- `fetch.py` — orchestrator; `_fetch_one()` (line ~185) is the natural place
  for a pre-fetch library check, ahead of the source loop.
- `fetch_crossref.py:67`, `fetch_istex.py:70`, `fetch_hal.py:72`,
  `fetch_scihub.py:36`, `fetch_unpaywall.py:27`, `fetch_url.py:22`,
  `fetch_libgen.py:121` — the current per-source `os.path.exists` skip logic
  (pattern to mirror; returns `status: "skipped"`).
- `config.py` — add Zotero config (DB path / API creds, enable flag).
- `utils.py` — home for a `zotero_lookup(doi, title)` helper.

## Design notes / decisions to make
- **Data source**: local Zotero SQLite DB (`zotero.sqlite`, read-only, no
  network, must handle Zotero's DB lock while the app is open — open with
  `?immutable=1` or copy) vs. the Zotero Web API (needs API key + library ID,
  works remotely). Recommend local SQLite first, API as optional fallback.
- **Match key**: DOI is authoritative (Zotero stores it in `itemDataValues`
  via the `DOI` field). Fall back to normalized title match only when DOI is
  absent.
- **Behavior on hit**: return a new `"skipped"` result (reuse the existing
  status so logs/summaries need no change) with a reason distinguishing
  "already in Zotero" from "already in papers/". Optionally record the Zotero
  attachment path.
- **Opt-in**: gate behind config (e.g. `ZOTERO_DB_PATH` set / `--check-zotero`
  flag) so users without Zotero are unaffected.
- Cross-check the existing `zotero-import` skill (PDF -> Zotero direction) for
  any reusable DB-access code before writing new SQLite queries.

## Actions
1. Add Zotero config to `config.py` (DB path or API creds; disabled by default).
2. Implement `zotero_lookup(doi, title) -> dict | None` in `utils.py`:
   query the Zotero SQLite DB for a matching item; return item metadata (incl.
   any attachment path) on hit, `None` on miss.
3. Wire a pre-fetch check into `fetch.py::_fetch_one` (and the single-download
   path) so a Zotero hit short-circuits to `"skipped"` before any source runs.
4. Add a `--check-zotero` CLI flag (and/or config enable) in `parse_args`.
5. Document the feature in `README.md` (English only).

## Test
- Write `tests/test_zotero_lookup.py` first (TDD red step): build a tiny
  temporary SQLite DB with Zotero's schema subset (itemData / itemDataValues /
  fields for DOI + title), assert `zotero_lookup` returns a hit for a present
  DOI and `None` for an absent one. Mark network-free (unit).
- Add a `fetch._fetch_one` test asserting a stubbed Zotero hit yields
  `status == "skipped"` without calling any source module.

## Verification
- [ ] `zotero_lookup` returns hit by DOI, miss otherwise, against a fixture DB.
- [ ] `_fetch_one` short-circuits to `"skipped"` on a Zotero hit; no source is
      invoked.
- [ ] Feature is opt-in: with Zotero disabled, behavior is byte-for-byte the
      current behavior.
- [ ] Read-only DB access does not corrupt or lock a live Zotero DB.

## Invariants
- Existing `PAPERS_DIR` filesystem skip logic keeps working unchanged.
- No new hard dependency for users who do not enable Zotero.
- `make check` (or the project's test command) passes; ruff check + format clean.

## Exit criteria
- With Zotero enabled and a DOI present in the library, DOIfetch skips the
  fetch and logs it as skipped-via-Zotero, invoking no download source.
- Opt-out path is default and preserves current behavior.
